recipeInstructions:
This is a recently invented Central Asian pilaf, dating from just after World War II. At first popular among teahouse pilaf cooks in eastern Uzbekistan, it's now cooked all over that country. Most people squeeze out the mild cooked garlic from the whole cloves and use it as a sauce for the pilaf.
1. Put oil in a large pot.
2. Add onions and saute over medium heat until light brown.
3. Add meat and stir until browned.
4. Add carrots and 5 cups water, and cook over medium-high heat until meat is tender, about 7 minutes.
5. Mix whole heads of garlic into stew.
6. Sprinkle rinsed rice over the top.
7. Add 8 cups water, taking care not to disturb the layering of rice and stew.
8. Boil uncovered until rice absorbs water, about 40-45 minutes.
9. When rice is done, heap it in the pot, cover with a lid, reduce heat to minimum, and steam for 25-30 minutes.
10. Serve 1 head garlic with each portion of pilaf. Makes 10-12 servings.
